\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 168.               Steptorhamphus}             Bunge
\par 

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By V. Feráková & P.D. Sell.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennial herbs with tuberous roots. Stems solitary, simple or branched. Leaves entire to pinnatifid, amplexicaul. Capitula few to numerous. Involucral bracts in several rows. Receptacle without scales. Ligules yellow or violet. Achenes compressed, with a very long, slender beak; pappus of 2 rows of simple hairs, the outer few, forming a very short fringe.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. S. tuberosus} (Jacq.) Grossh., {\i Fl. Kavk.}{\b  4}: 258 (1934) ({\i Lactuca cretica} Desf.). Stem 40-60(-100) cm, sometimes branched above. Lower leaves entire to runcinate-pinnatifid, sagittate-amplexicaul, hairy; uppermost cauline lanceolate, entire. Capitula 1-2. Involucral bracts up to 40 mm, lanceolate to ovate, usually purplish-tinged, glabrous or nearly so. Ligules yellow. Achene 6-15 mm; body elliptical, 1- to 3-ribbed, minutely hairy and rugulose; beak pale, 1½-3 times as long as body.{\i  S. part of Balkan peninsula and Aegean region; Krym.} Bu Cr Gr Rs (K).
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  Plants with lilac or purple ligules but otherwise similar to {\b 1} occur in S.W. Asia; they have been reported from Krym, but have not been seen there in recent years.
